---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import Wordmark from "../../components/Wordmark.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/+$/, "");
const url = (path: string) => `${base}/${path.replace(/^\/+/, "")}`;
---

<Base
  title="Support — VoiceDrop"
  description="VoiceDrop support, setup guide, and FAQ. Contact ukint-vs@proton.me."
>
  <Wordmark withMark />

  <h1>Support</h1>
  <p>Setup guide, common questions, and how to reach the developer.</p>

  <div class="contact-card">
    <strong>Contact</strong>
    <p>
      Email
      <a href="mailto:ukint-vs@proton.me?subject=VoiceDrop%20support"
        >ukint-vs@proton.me</a
      >. Replies usually within a day or two.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Setting up the keyboard</h2>
  <p>
    VoiceDrop ships with a keyboard extension that lets you dictate
    voice-to-text from inside any messaging app. Setup is a one-time thing:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      iOS
      <strong
        >Settings → General → Keyboard → Keyboards → Add New Keyboard</strong
      >
       → select VoiceDrop.
    </li>
    <li>
      Tap the newly-added VoiceDrop row → toggle
      <strong>Allow Full Access</strong> on.
    </li>
    <li>
      In any app that accepts text, tap the globe key (<span class="kbd"
        >🌐</span
      >) on the keyboard → switch to VoiceDrop.
    </li>
    <li>
      Tap the big red mic button. VoiceDrop opens, you dictate, silence
      auto-stops the recording.
    </li>
    <li>
      Read the transcript. When satisfied, tap the
      <strong>‹ [App Name]</strong> breadcrumb in the iOS top-left corner.
      You're back in your messaging app with the transcript inserted at your
      cursor.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently asked</h2>

  <h3>Why does the keyboard need Full Access?</h3>
  <p>
    The keyboard needs to read the transcribed text from a shared App Group
    storage slot — that's the only reason. It does not transmit keystrokes,
    record audio, make network requests, or include any analytics. Audio
    recording and transcription happen exclusively in the main VoiceDrop app.
    The keyboard is a thin text-insertion client. See the
    <a href={url("privacy/")}>privacy policy</a> for the full breakdown.
  </p>

  <h3>Does my voice leave the device?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Transcription runs on Apple's Neural Engine using the Parakeet model,
    which was downloaded once to your device during onboarding. After that,
    VoiceDrop makes no network requests at all. No audio is uploaded. No
    transcripts are uploaded. No usage analytics are collected.
  </p>

  <h3>Why is the first recording so slow?</h3>
  <p>
    The Parakeet model (~600 MB) downloads from Hugging Face the first time you
    open the app. The <strong>very first launch</strong> also compiles the model
    for the Neural Engine, which takes about 15–20 seconds. Subsequent cold
    launches load from the compiled cache in under a second. While Parakeet is
    loading (or downloading), VoiceDrop falls back to Apple Speech — lower
    quality but instant. Once Parakeet is warm, it's ~70× realtime — a
    one-second clip transcribes in under 15 ms.
  </p>

  <h3>How do I disable auto-stop on silence?</h3>
  <p>
    VoiceDrop → <strong>Settings tab → Silence detection</strong>. Toggle off.
    In-app recordings then require you to tap the mic button to stop. (Action
    Button and keyboard flows still auto-stop — they run without a visible stop
    button, so silence is how they know you're done.)
  </p>

  <h3>How do I uninstall everything?</h3>
  <p>
    Delete the app like any other iOS app. All transcripts, model cache,
    settings, and shared storage are cleared on uninstall. Nothing of yours
    remains on any server (because nothing was ever there).
  </p>

  <h3>Which languages work?</h3>
  <p>
    VoiceDrop ships with two on-device speech engines. Parakeet TDT v3 is the
    default and covers 25 European languages with the lowest word-error rate.
    Qwen3-ASR is the alternative engine and adds 14 more including Arabic,
    Chinese (Mandarin and Cantonese), Japanese, Korean, Hindi, Persian, Thai,
    Vietnamese, and Indonesian. Combined, <strong>39 languages</strong> are
    available.
  </p>
  <p>
    The full list: Arabic, Bulgarian, Cantonese, Chinese, Croatian, Czech,
    Danish, Dutch, English, Estonian, Filipino, Finnish, French, German, Greek,
    Hindi, Hungarian, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Latvian,
    Lithuanian, Macedonian, Malay, Norwegian, Persian, Polish, Portuguese,
    Romanian, Russian, Slovak, Slovenian, Spanish, Swedish, Thai, Turkish,
    Ukrainian, Vietnamese.
  </p>
  <p>
    In <strong>Auto</strong> mode the active engine detects the language
    per-recording. You can also pin a specific language in
    <strong>Settings → Language</strong>; languages not supported by the active
    engine fall back to auto-detect.
  </p>

  <h3>The transcript is wrong. What can I do?</h3>
  <p>
    During the keyboard flow, tap the
    <strong>Try again</strong> button on the done state. That discards the
    current transcript and starts a fresh recording, without returning to your
    messaging app. If a specific word is consistently wrong (your name, a place,
    technical jargon), email the developer — custom vocabulary is planned for a
    future Pro tier.
  </p>

  <h2>Reporting a bug</h2>
  <p>Any of these are worth a quick email:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Crashes or freezes</li>
    <li>Transcription that's consistently wrong for a specific phrase</li>
    <li>Keyboard doesn't insert text after you return to the host app</li>
    <li>UI that's confusing or requires guessing</li>
    <li>Battery drain during long recordings</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you reach the app's Settings tab, tap
    <strong>Send feedback</strong> and it'll pre-fill your build number, device
    model, and language mode so replies don't need back-and-forth. Nothing about
    what you dictated is ever included.
  </p>
</Base>

<style>
  ul {
    padding-left: var(--space-lg);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-md);
  }

  li {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .contact-card {
    margin: var(--space-2xl) 0;
    padding: 20px var(--space-lg);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  }

  .contact-card p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .contact-card strong {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
</style>
